<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="Structured_CPDs">Structured CPDs</span></h1>
<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Overview:_Structured_CPDs">Overview: Structured CPDs</span></h2>
<p>Tabular representation: works well in a simple case, but if there are many parents of a node (say, k), then the number of entries are O($$2^k$$), so not really suitable.</p>
<h3> <span class="mw-headline" id="Context-specific_independence">Context-specific independence</span></h3>
<p>Independence only occurs when Z = c:</p>
<p>$$P(X,Y \mid Z, c) = P(X \mid Z,c) P(Y \mid Z,c)$$</p>
<p>$$P(X \mid Y, Z, c) = P(X \mid Z, c)$$</p>
<p>$$P(Y \mid X, Z, c) = P(Y \mid Z, c)$$</p>
<p>One example: Deterministic OR, where these are independent</p>
<p>$$(X \perp Y&#95;1 \mid y^1&#95;2)$$, i.e. $$(X \perp Y&#95;1 \mid y&#95;2, 1)$$</p>
<p>$$(Y&#95;1 \perp Y&#95;2 \mid x^0)$$</p>
<p>Neither of these would hold for a general-purpose CPD.</p>
<p>Conventions followed:</p>
<p>$$X&#95;i^0 = 0, X&#95;i^1 = 1$$</p>
